<td valign="top" style="padding-right:30px; padding-left:20px;">
<div id="Idea_4081"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/4081-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_4081">An Immodest Proposal&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/9532-4049">Brian Stewart</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">1 day ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">	For all of the tiniest fractions we can recognize as we drift forward through time, there are but very few precious times when we can remove ourselves from our own immediate circumstances and revel in the significance that, whether we like it or not, every single moment of our existence, indeed, of all existence has led us to this moment.  If we concentrate enough, and focus all of our energy, we can watch all of the universe’s energy work in wondrous unison.  Through the wonders of technology, we can freeze a particle of sand indefinitely in the neck of an hourglass, trapped in a nebulous area mankind has never explored before, that is, the bridge between what constitutes the past, present, and future.<br/>	There are precious few moments as time creeps ever forward, that we are granted perspective as to how the actions of the day will affect the goals we hope to accomplish.  In the Information Age, as technology outpaces itself as quickly as it can proliferate, any heuristic approach to reasonably predict the nature of society only one generation away becomes riddled with the complexities of the vast changes we have experienced in society over the previous generation.  And while the raw, pluralist nature of the internet allows us to examine all issues through the prism of multiculturalism when utilized efficiently, the equal and opposite reaction holds true as well; the ability to manipulate the human understandings of time, power, propriety, and truth are determining how we must adapt to survive in increasingly unfamiliar surroundings.<br/>	To write off this phenomenon as an inconvenient side effect of a powerful communication tool is to cast a blind eye to the nature of an untamed Beast that is consuming the written word at an exponential rate, democratizing the nature of journalistic integrity, and obfuscating the closest approximations to truth amongst an ever-expanding universe of insignificance and distraction.  The transparency that we seek is impossible to achieve without removing the filters of disenfranchisement, obscurity, and most importantly, fear - both of the American Government at large and of an unprecedented technological implement that is reshaping the average citizen’s working frame of their role in a properly functioning Republic.  <br/>	There is significant momentum at this critical juncture in history.  We have witnessed, in less than two decades since the greatest hegemonic power shift since 1648, the ability to redefine our Principles into any form to justify any Behavior.  If we, as a United people, wish to thrive in a unipolar world, we must first regain our Legitimacy.  Ours is a nation torn asunder in bipartisanship argument; what image do we project to the populations that have no other choice but to pay attention when we speak?  If the United States can not create peace within its Capitol, what chance have we to promote peace in the Middle East?<br/>	We are moving forward into uncharted realms of science, technology, and political power.  The foremost question regarding the governmental transition into cyberspace is not that of function, but rather of Legitimacy.  Giving access to a government that people distrust through a medium in which it is far to easy to manipulate the senses means little to disenfranchised populations who have witnessed unending political and economic scandals that showcase the greed and inhumanity of our most prominent citizens.  We shall not be placated with glorified Glasnost.<br/>	I propose a venture that many would claim impossible, more would claim infeasible, and few could reasonably be expected to put their weight behind: a new Constitution.  In this era, the American people lack direction, hope, and belief in the ideals that were put forth by wise men who never could have contemplated the vastness of the realization of their dream.  If we can not unite as One to define which principles we wish to truly stand for above all others, then what good is all of the power in the World?  We have the ability to connect all of America, we have the tools to gather information at an ever-increasing pace, what we lack is the imagination to utilize those tools for projects of unprecedented magnitude.  <br/>	We can not allow our foresight to be artificially constrained by attempting to logically grapple with the mental image of futuristic technologies.  It is but a mere distraction to the greater ideals we should wish to instill in future generations to promote cooperation, trust, and patriotism.  As a country we have proven before the fruits of cooperation and unity, and we should seek a project worthy of the greatest scholars, engineers, and philosophers, tempered openly by the will of the people so that as we venture forth into the great unknowns that we know the future has in store, we may do so with the confidence that our causes are Just, our hearts are Pure, and that we are wholly and shall forever remain, United.<br/><br/>Brian Stewart<br/>BA, Political Science<br/>New College of Florida, 2000</div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_4081" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_4081', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2294&topicID=4081')">Comments (5)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_4081"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2294">Legal & Policy Challenges</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_4081"></div>
</div></td>
</tr>
